column168: SequenceEvent: The package was brought to our attention as it had a wet surface at the bottom and slight leakage. SequenceEvent: Package was picked up from a driver on the day of 12/14/23 and brought back to the station. Upon arrival of QA Calvin Pudela (12/15/23 @ 12:00PM), a noticeable odor of alcohol was coming from the pail. Upon further investigation of the HAZMAT Pail, I covered the opening with tape so I could test if the seal was actually broken or not. Once I flipped the pail over, I noticed that there was a slight amount of liquid coming out. Then I started my processing of HAZMAT package. DescribePack: There is a cap built into the top cap for the pail of denatured alcohol. The cap appears to have been opened and no longer seems to close/seal. DurationRel: 6 and MitigateEffect: I taped the cap of the pail opening to avoid anymore of the smell escaping.

column168: On December 13, 2023, one (1) 330-gallon tote of UN1760 was crushed in transit and released approximately fifteen (15) gallons of product to the trailer interior and dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted site. FCE personnel successfully transferred the contents from the damaged 330-gallon tote to a new 330-gallon tote for further shipment and processing. Crews utilized hand tools to cut up the damaged tote for waste, and they utilized a neutralizing solution and absorbent pads to remediate the impacted dock floor. Four (4) 55-gallon drums containing the cut-up tote, spent absorbent pads, damaged metal fittings, and impacted cardboard were generated as waste and staged in the terminal's waste holding room.

XPO Logistics terminal LLB experienced a NA1993 CORR21334A release from a 230-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2-gallons of material released to a 2’ x 2’ area of the trailer floor and a 1’ x 1’ area of the concrete dock due to a bad valve. The shipment was discovered during sort operations. A metal can inside of the box leaked liquid that was bubbling, steaming and had corroded away a large portion of the metal can. column168: XPO Logistics terminal LLA experienced a UN1866 ELAN-Cast P 300 S RTC Low Odor release from a 330-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 50-gallons of material released to the entire trailer floor as well as a 30’ x 20’ area of the concrete lot below due to the trailer wall puncturing the tote. The puncture was patched with wood to stop the release and the material was transferred into a new tote for shipment on. The free-standing liquid material was collected with a drum vac into (2) 55-gallon metal drums. Floor dry was then deployed and worked into the impacted areas and then collected into a third 55-gallon metal drum. The punctured tote was patched with absorbent pads & chemical tape. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On 12/15/2023 at approximately 1345  , Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 68727 at the station location in Groveland, reporting a herbicide spill.  The shipment consisted of one plastic container that shipped inside of a fiberboard box. The shipment was discovered leaking, initially the cause was unknown.  The shipment was discovered leaking during delivery and was returned to the station,  Further investigation revealed that the top was not secure on the bottle, causing the spillage. An online safety data sheet was located by Dangerous Goods Administration and it revealed that the commodity was  classified as a regulated corrosive shipment, though not prepared in accordance with IATA Regulations.  The shipment is being held pending an FAA investigation.

column168: While in transit, (1) box containing (2) 1-gallon bottles of Blue Whale Muriatic Acid (UN1789) became crushed as a result of inadequate preparation for transportation. During the off-loading process, the damaged, crushed product began leaking onto the concrete dock floor; a total amount of 1-gallon. A Contractor neutralized the release using Kolorsafe Liquid Acid Neutralizer before absorbing the liquid and containerizing the spill debris into the proper UN-rated shipping container (a vented 55-gallon fiber drum). Additionally, the pallet in which the load was shipped on was also cut-up and containerized for waste disposal. Lastly, the impacted box that the leaking bottles shipped in was neutralized and containerized for waste disposal. No storm drains, waterways, or soil were impacting by the release.

column168: On December 8, 2023, one (1) 2.5 gallon jug of ZeroTol 2.0 was crushed in transit and released approximately less than one (<1) gallon of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Ten West Environmental (TWE) to remediate the impacted site. TWE personnel utilized hand tools, absorbents, and soda ash to remediate the ZeroTol-impacted impacted trailer. The crew de palletized, re palletized, and shrink wrapped the freight for the customer. The damaged jug and all impacted debris were collected and containerized into two (2) 55-gallon poly vented drums and stored on site for transport and disposal.

XPO Logistics terminal XQC experienced a UN1760 Gunsmoke release from a box containing (2) 2.5-gallon poly jugs. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2.5-gallons of material released from one of the jugs due to a forklift puncture. Absorbents and pH Up neutralizer were utilized to clean and neutralize the release. The empty damaged drum, impacted absorbents, PPE, and impacted cardboard were containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On December 15, 2023, one (1) 55-gallon drum containing UN1789 was damaged and released approximately two (2) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from American Compliance Technologies (ACT) to remediate the impacted site. ACT personnel utilized hand tools, absorbents, and soda ash to remediate the sulfuric acid-impacted impacted trailer floor and soil under the trailer. Crews tightened the bung and the leak stopped. Crews secured the drum upright to the trailer wall and the driver continued on to the terminal. Utilizing hand tools, the ACT crew was able to excavate the impacted soil. All impacted debris were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum that was taken by ACT.

column168: Veolia employees were at Veolia's 10-day intransit facility in Gurabo, PR when they detected a strong odor coming from one of the trailers. Further investigation revealed that a 55 gallon drum had over pressurized and spilled chemicals. The spill was contained within the trailer and did not exit out or under the trailer. column169: Veolia has been picking up from this customer for about 5 years on a frequency of once every 1-2 weeks from the customer's waste storage area and has never had this issue before. The customer would put an inhibitor into the containers when they were placed in the storage area and they would sit in storage for at least a week until Veolia picked them up. The customer recently demolished their on-site storage area for building additions and requested Veolia to come weekly for service pick ups. Historically, the customer would apply hydroquinone as an inhibitor to the waste at least 48 hours prior to Veolia's pick up service to ensure neutralization and any reaction is completed prior to offering the drums for transportation. Following the incident, discussion with the customer revealed that the hydroquinone was added to the waste drum on the same day Veolia picked up the waste container. The hydroquinone inhibitor should be applied at least 48 hours prior to our pick up service to ensure the neutralization reaction is completed. The practice of the 48 hour waiting period was done in all previous service pick ups with no incidents. The customer has agreed to apply the hydroquinone inhibitor on Fridays to ensure the neutralization reaction is completed prior to Veolia picking up the waste on Mondays. The Veolia employees will monitor this procedure very closely and validate in advance the date and time of inhibitor application prior to pick up the drums.

column42: AMMONIUM NITRATE EMULSION OR AMMONIUM NITRATE SUSPENSION OR AMMONIUM NITRATE GEL, INTERMEDIATE FOR BLASTING EXPLOSIVES
column168: On 11/30/2023, 45,660 pounds of Ammonium Nitrate Emulsion (ANE) was loaded into trailer 974 through the rearmost hatch. After loading was completed, the rear hatch was not closed and latched by the loader.  On 12/1/2023, the driver coupled to the trailer and departed Barry, IL and drove to Buckley Powder Company in Hermann, MO.  The driver arrived, unloaded into the product tower, and traveled back in reverse order on the same route.  The trailer was uncoupled Barry, IL. Employees at site observed ANE residue on the side of the trailer.  Buckley Powder Company found spots of ANE residue on their private gravel road totaling less than ten (10) pounds, which they cleaned up and disposed of properly.  It is estimated 5,247 pounds of ANE was lost in transit between Barry, IL and Hermann, MO.   It was raining on 12/1/2023. Dyno Nobel employees inspected the roadways of IL 106 and US 54 and there was not any evidence of residue on the roadway. The Buckley Powder manager inspected Loutre Bend Rd and did not observe residue on the road.
column169: The company will conduct refresher training on pre/post-trip inspections, and the site supervisor will review the company employee accountability program with the drivers.  The company will continue with the HazMat spot checks to ensure compliance with the hazardous materials regulations.

column168: While in transit, (2) 55DF's containing Sulfuric Acid 1.500 (UN1830) fell over as a result of inadequate preparation for transportation forcing the bung caps to loosen and release 20-gallons of product on the pallet, the trailer floor, and the asphalt beneath the trailer. Contractors neutralized the release using sodium bicarbonate and solidified the liquid with oil dry. The impacted pallet was cut-up and containerized with the rest of the spill debris into (3) 55DF's for waste disposal. No storm drains, water ways, or soil were impacted by the release.

While unloading a pallet of waste from a trailer at Veolia's ten day intransit facility, a Veolia employee heard a pop and realized the forks on the forklift were protruding out of the back of the pallet and punctured a 15 gallon 1H1 drum of flammable liquid located on the pallet behind the one he was moving. Approximately 100 ml of the material leaked out before the hole closed on itself. The employee moved the forklift away from the area and shut it off, then proceeded to contain the spill with absorbent. The employee and the Veolia site manager then donned correct PPE and promptly overpacked the container and cleaned up the spill area.
column169: The Veolia employee needs to be aware of the length of their forks on the forklift in reference to the material they are handling and ensure that their forks do not protrude out the back of the pallet they are working on. Also whenever possible use a spotter to ensure safe loading practices.

XPO Logistics terminal LSL experienced a UN1993 WCW6400 Combination Product release from a 330-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to complete cleanup and a liquid tote transfer. Contractors arrived onsite and liaised with onsite LSP contact, Jay Hardy. Crew confirmed approximately 1.5-ounces of product released to the tote lid only which was padded up with an absorbent pad. The release was caused by a crack to the top corner of the tote as a result of improper loading. The product was then transferred via pump, at the requested of the LSP, into a new tote for shipment on. The damaged tote was then cut up and containerized along with all impacted absorbent pads and PPE into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.
